Excellent.

This is where we stop being "developers" and become Software Engineers.

Most tutorials completely skip this document.

Most AI tools also skip it.

But companies like Amazon, Microsoft, Uber, and Stripe don't.

They define the Domain Model before they define APIs.

Why?

Look at these two sentences:

User places an order.
Customer purchases products.

Are they the same?

Almost.

But in software engineering,

User

and

Customer

can be two completely different entities.

Without a Domain Model, every developer starts using different names.

Eventually your code becomes

User

Customer

Buyer

Client

Member

Account

all meaning the same thing.

That becomes a nightmare.

What is a Domain?

A Domain is simply

The business we are building.

Our domain is

Ecommerce

Inside Ecommerce there are many smaller domains.

Authentication

Catalog

Shopping

Payments

Orders

Shipping

Administration
Why This Document Exists

The Domain Model answers

What exists in our business?

Not

How to code it.

Not

Which API.

Not

Which table.

Business only.

Imagine Amazon

Amazon doesn't think

POST /orders

They think

Customer

↓

Shopping Cart

↓

Checkout

↓

Payment

↓

Order

↓

Shipment

↓

Delivery

That's called

Business Flow.